text: Stereoselective Total Synthesis of the Dimeric Naphthoquinonopyrano-γ-lactone (−)-Crisamicin A: Introducing the Dimerization Site by a Late-Stage Hartwig Borylation Julia Kopp and Reinhard Brückner* ABSTRACT: The ﬁrst stereoselective total synthesis of the dimeric naphthoquinonopyrano-γ-lactone (−)-crisamicin A was realized (13 steps, 5% overall yield). 1,4,5-Trimethoxynaphthalene, reached in ﬁve known steps, was brominated at C-3 to install a but-3-enoic ester by an ensuing Heck coupling. An asymmetric Sharpless dihydroxylation followed and gave a β-hydroxy-γ-lactone with >99.9% ee. Its OH substituent and acetaldehyde established the dihydropyran ring in a completely diastereoselective oxa-Pictet−Spengler cyclization. The 2,3- fused anisole moiety allowed the C5−H bond under Hartwig’s conditions to be borylated. This set the stage for engaging the resulting C5−B bond in an oxidative dimerization, which led to a binaphthohydroquinon-5-yl. The latter was advanced to synthetic crisamicin A by a double CAN oxidation (→ a binaphthoquinon-5-yl) and a double demethylation. N aphthoquinonopyrano-γ-lactones (for examples, see

Figure 1) have attracted attention in medicine, pharmacology, and chemistry.1 They act against Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, pathogenic fungi, and yeasts and may exhibit antiviral or anticancer activities.2 Naphthoquino- nopyrano-γ-lactones from nature may be monomeric (e.g., 1a,3 1b,4 ent-1a5) or dimeric (e.g., 3,6 57,8). In addition, some natural products have the structure of benzylic hydrogenolysis products of naphthoquinonopyrano-γ-lactones, no matter whether they are monomeric (cf. 29 vs ent-1a5) or dimeric (cf. 410 vs 36).11 In the following, we disclose the ﬁrst stereoselective total the dimeric naphthoquinonopyrano-γ-lactone synthesis of (−)-crisamicin A7,8 (5). As a natural product, this compound was isolated by Nelson et al.7 and Ling et al.8 It was the main bioactive ingredient of a potpourri of compounds produced by the soil bacterium Micromonospora purpureochromogenes subsp. halotolerans from the Philippines.7,8 (−)-Crisamicin A is highly soluble in DMA, DMF, and DMSO, moderately soluble in CH3CN, EtOAc, CHCl3, AcOH, and acetone, yellow in acid and purple in base.7 (−)-Crisamicin A is active against Gram- positive bacteria,7 B16 melanoma cells,12 and the Herpes simplex,12 Vaccinia,12 and Vesicular stomatitis viruses.12 The 7), 1H NMR,8 as well as 13C molecular formula (C32H22O12 NMR spectroscopy,13 ORD,8 and the Cotton eﬀect8,14 in the ORD curve revealed that (−)-crisamicin A (5) is a naphthoquinonopyrano-γ-lactone dimer composed of two identical subunits with the absolute conﬁgurations depicted in Figure

It held the promise of proceeding in an innovative manner from a monomeric to a dimeric naphthoquinonopyrano-γ-lactone here. It also entailed the hope of being useful beyond this speciﬁc objective. The ensuing retrosynthetic simpliﬁcations are akin to our approach to (+)-γ-actinorhodin:21 (1) The tetracyclic building block 6 should stem from an oxa-Pictet−Spengler

cyclization of the hydroxylactone 7;27 as often28 its steric course was hardly predictable. (2) The hydroxylactone 7 should arise by an asymmetric Sharpless dihydroxylation/in situ lactoniza- tion from a trans-conﬁgurated β,γ-unsaturated ester 8.29 (3) Such esters result from Heck couplings between a but-3-enoic ester and an aryl halide,30 here the bromonaphthalene 9. 9 would be made from NBS and 1,4,5-trimethoxynaphthalene44 (10). The latter had been prepared in ﬁve steps from 1,5- dihydroxynaphthalene (“route A”31−34 = our route) or in four steps from 1,4-dimethoxybenzene (“route B”35−37). We synthesized three trans-conﬁgured type-8 esters, namely, a methyl ester (8a, 59%), benzyl ester (8b, 91%), and tert-butyl ester (8c, 75%), by the Heck couplings30,38,39 shown in Scheme 1. The same hydroxylactone 7 was reached via the dihydroxyester 13 and F3CCO2H by being reﬂuxed in toluene (55% yield, >99.9% ee), albeit less eﬃciently (36% overall from 8c/iso-8a).

The chemistry of Scheme 2 ended with a “simple” oxa-Pictet− Spengler cyclization, incorporating acetaldehyde in the presence 48 (7 → 6; 88% yield). In an “elaborate variant” of of BF3 that cyclization, it concurred with tert-butyl ester cleavage and lactonization (13 → 6; 67% yield). Both procedures delivered the naphthohydroquinonopyrano-γ-lactone 6 with perfect 3a,5trans-selectivity.49 Disconcerted by the lack of precedence for such a pleasing outcome,28,50 we tried many other oxa- Pictet−Spengler conditions before obtaining an inseparable mixture of naphthohydroquinonopyrano-γ-lactone diaster- eomers 6, 5-epi-6, and 3a-epi-6.51 The newly formed compounds 5-epi-6 and 3a-epi-6 were the 3a,5cis- and 3a,11btrans-isomer of the desired diastereomer 6 (3a,5trans,3a,11bcis) according to 1H NMR similarities to model compounds.48

Having met the stereochemical exigencies of our endeavor (Scheme 2), the naphthohydroquinonopyrano-γ-lactone 6 was dimerized in steps (a) and (b) of Scheme 3. Step (a), a Hartwig borylation, succeeded with pinacolborane, 2.5 mol % of [{Ir(μ- OMe)COD}2], and 5 mol % of 4,4′-di-tert-butyl-2,2′- dipyridyl.52,53 It activated the least hindered naphthyl−H bond of substrate 6 with perfect regioselectivity; that is, it attacked meta relative to both the MeO group and the annulated ring. The expected boronic ester 14 was so labile that it could not be puriﬁed by ﬂash chromatography but only by ﬁltration over silica. This measure reduced the time expenditure for the ensuing step (b), a Pd-catalyzed autoxidative homocoupling “under operationally simple conditions”,54 from 1 day to 2.5 h and increased the yield of the desired binaphthyl 15in an inseparable 77:23 mixture with Ph3POto 46% over two Scheme 3. We managed to crystallize compound 15 so that its 3D structure could be proven by the ﬁrst X-ray structural analysis of a dimeric naphthohydroquinonopyrano-γ-lactone.

Oxidizing the binaphthyl 15 (accompanied by Ph3PO) with (NH4)2[Ce(NO3)6] delivered the naphthoquinonopyrano-γ- lactone dimethyl ether 1656 in 65% yield (Scheme 3). Gratifyingly, it was separable from Ph3PO by column chromatography using pentane/acetone as an eluent.57 In CH2Cl2, the ether functions of compound 16 were cleaved 21,58 (→ 67% 559) but unselectively with smoothly with AlCl3 58,60 (→ 5 + a structurally similar contaminant, which was BCl3 inseparable). The 1H NMR spectrum (500.10 MHz, CDCl3, CD2Cl2) and 13C NMR spectrum (125.75 MHz, CDCl3, CD2Cl2) of our totally synthetic (−)-crisamicin A (5) matched their precedents from isolated (−)-crisamicin A (58,13). In conclusion, we realized the ﬁrst stereoselective total the dimeric naphthoquinonopyrano-γ-lactone synthesis of (−)-crisamicin A (5). Starting from 1,5-dihydroxynaphthalene (which gave 46% of the trimethoxynaphthalene 10 in ﬁve steps;31 not depicted in Scheme 1), it comprised 13 steps and https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.orglett.0c01078 Org. totaled 5% yield. A key feature of our approach is that binaphthyl formation occurred late and aﬀected the naphthalene moiety of compound 6, which had been unf unctionalized at the dimerization site up to that stage (Scheme 3). This naphthalene’s C7−H bond was activated by a regioselective Hartwig borylation, upon which the resulting naphthylboronic pinacolate 14 was dimerized oxidatively (→ biaryl 15). Quinone formation (→ 16) and ether cleavage (→ 5) ﬁnished our route. It appears as if Hartwig borylation/C−C homocoupling tandem reactions like this study’s sequence (6 → 14 → biaryl 15) have not been used previously for reaching symmetrical condensed biaryls with functional groups.61 Nevertheless, accesses of that kind to “all sorts of symmetrical biaryls with functional groups” are conceivable. These might even include symmetrical condensed heterocyclic biaryls with functional groups (or precursors thereof), for example, a bi(quinolin-6- yl),62 a bi(pyrido[1,2-a]pyrimidin-8-yl),63 a bi(benzothiazol-6- yl),64 or a bi(indol-5-yl);65 none of these compounds was synthesized by this strategy. *sı Supporting Information The Supporting Information is available free of charge at https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acs.orglett.0c01078.
